threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This mipsel32 ELF binary is an IoT botnet agent, likely a variant of Mirai or Gafgyt/Bashlite. It features multiple DDoS attack vectors (SYN, UDP, and SSDP floods) and network scanning capabilities. Key malicious behaviors include: 1) SSDP discovery scanning (sub_408970) using 'M-SEARCH' strings to identify vulnerable devices; 2) C2 communication with a hardcoded IP 81.94.156.24 (sub_40a904); 3) Process termination logic (sub_4093f0) designed to eliminate competing malware from the host; 4) Daemonization via fork() and setsid() with I/O redirection to /dev/null (sub_40fd24). The binary uses fake User-Agents (Chrome 60/Windows) to masquerade malicious traffic.
